      "thumbnail": "https://i.postimg.cc/8CYQVHDj/1771519254820.png",
      "content": "<h2><span style=\"color: rgb(45, 106, 79);\">Introduction</span></h2><p>Rohidas Singh Nag (5 February 1934 ‚Äì 30 December 2012) was an Indian linguist, writer, and poet best known as the inventor of the Mundari Bani script. He dedicated his life to preserving and promoting the Mundari language and is respectfully known as ‚ÄúOl Guru‚Äù among his community.</p><p>His work gave the Mundari language its own writing system and strengthened the cultural identity of the Munda people.</p><p>---</p><h2><span style=\"color: rgb(45, 106, 79);\">Early Life</span></h2><p>Rohidas Singh Nag was born on 5 February 1934 in Chandua village, Mayurbhanj district, in present-day Odisha. He grew up in a tribal region where Mundari was widely spoken but did not have its own standardized script.</p><p>From a young age, he showed deep interest in language and culture.</p><p>---</p><h2><span style=\"color: rgb(45, 106, 79);\">Early Innovation: Creation of Mundari Bani (1949)</span></h2><p>In 1949, while still a school student, Nag began developing what would later become:</p><p>Mundari Bani</p><p>He first wrote the alphabet on the walls of his school using clay. This marked the beginning of his lifelong effort to create a proper writing system for the Mundari language.</p><p>Why This Was Important</p><p></p><ul><li>He was still a student at the time.</li><li>He studied the sounds of the Mundari language carefully.</li><li>He wanted to avoid using Roman, Odia, or Devanagari scripts.</li></ul><p></p><p>This early effort laid the foundation for a complete and independent script.</p><p>---</p><h2><span style=\"color: rgb(45, 106, 79);\">Development of the Script</span></h2><p><span style=\"font-weight: bold; color: rgb(27, 67, 50);\">1953 ‚Äì Expansion</span></p><p>In 1953, he expanded and improved the original alphabet. He refined the shapes of the letters and improved sound representation.</p><p><span style=\"font-weight: bold; color: rgb(27, 67, 50);\">1980 ‚Äì Standardization</span></p><p>After years of improvement, Nag finalized the script in 1980. He simplified the alphabet and selected 27 standard letters for regular use.</p><p>In the same year, he presented the script to the then Chief Minister of Odisha, J. B. Patnaik.</p><p>He also submitted a formal memorandum requesting constitutional recognition for the Munda language. This was an important step toward official acceptance.</p><p>---</p><p><span style=\"font-weight: bold; color: rgb(27, 67, 50);\">1999 ‚Äì National Appeal</span></p><p>In 1999, Rohidas Singh Nag and other activists submitted a memorandum to the President of India. They requested that the Mundari language be granted constitutional recognition.</p><p>This showed that Nag was not only a script inventor but also a strong advocate for language rights and indigenous recognition at the national level.</p><p>---</p><h2><span style=\"color: rgb(45, 106, 79);\">Educational and Cultural Impact</span></h2><p>By 2004, several schools in Odisha had started using Mundari Bani for teaching. This helped:</p><p></p><ul><li>Promote mother-tongue education</li><li>Preserve cultural heritage</li><li>Encourage written literature in Mundari</li></ul><p></p><p>The script became a symbol of pride and identity for the Munda community.</p><p>---</p><h2><span style=\"color: rgb(45, 106, 79);\">Digital Recognition</span></h2><p>The script, also known as Nag Mundari, was officially added to the Unicode Standard in 2021‚Äì2022. This inclusion allows the script to be used in digital platforms, computers, and smartphones.</p><p>This ensured that Mundari Bani entered the modern digital era.</p><p>---</p><h2><span style=\"color: rgb(45, 106, 79);\">Legacy</span></h2><p>Rohidas Singh Nag passed away on 30 December 2012 at the age of 78. However, his contribution continues to influence language preservation movements.</p><p>Today, he is remembered as:</p><p></p><ul><li>The inventor of Mundari Bani</li><li>A protector of tribal linguistic heritage</li><li>A leader in the Mundari language movement</li></ul><p></p><p>His work remains one of the most important achievements in the history of indigenous languages in India.</p><p>---</p>"
